# Getting Started

## 1. Install dependencies

```bash
npm install
npm run build
```

## 2. Configure environment

```bash
cp .env.example .env
```

Edit `.env` and fill in:
- `JIRA_BASE_URL` — e.g. `https://your-org.atlassian.net`
- `JIRA_EMAIL` — the email you use to log into Jira
- `JIRA_API_TOKEN` — create one at id.atlassian.com/manage-profile/security/api-tokens
- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` — create one at console.anthropic.com

## 3. Configure WORKFLOW.md

Open `WORKFLOW.md` and set `tracker.space_key` to your Jira space key
(the prefix on your issue IDs — e.g. if issues are `ZMATA-1`, the key is `ZMATA`).

Also set `tracker.active_states` to match the exact status names in your Jira space.
To find them: open any issue in Jira and look at the Status field.

## 4. Install GitHub CLI and authenticate

Symphony uses `gh` to open pull requests.

```bash
brew install gh
gh auth login
```

## 5. Start Symphony

```bash
npm run phony
```

## 6. Create a ticket

1. Go to your Jira space
2. Click **Create** and write an issue with a clear title and description
3. Move the issue to one of your configured `active_states` (e.g. "In Progress")
4. Symphony will pick it up within 30 seconds

## 7. Monitor progress

Open the dashboard in your browser:

```
http://127.0.0.1:3000
```

This shows active agent sessions, retry queue, and token usage.
It auto-refreshes every 10 seconds.

Logs are written to:
- `symphony.log` — full structured log (JSON)
- `symphony-summary.log` — human-readable session summaries grouped by issue
